			<tr>
				<td colspan="2" height="100%" valign="top"><span class="postbody">Don't take it personal.  You will be barked at.  Someone's gonna step on your feelings.  Science of War has a fairly unique raiding style and is a very demanding organization.  Expect a "vovagram".  Expect someone to jump on you for your positioning.  We don't want you to get mad.  We don't want you to get upset.  We just want you to follow the instructions given.
<br />

<br />
If you're unsure, ask.  Use your chain of command.  If you don't know the answer to a question you have, immediately ask your group leader.  If instructions are unclear, immediately ask your group leader.
<br />

<br />
Stay buffed.  Individual buffs are YOUR responsibility.  Nobody's gonna gripe at you for asking for buffs.  People will be upset if you die because you didn't ask for the buffs you need to stay alive.  In that same vein, tell your group leader if a group buff wears off.  In most cases, the request has been put in for a renewal, but it won't hurt to ask.
<br />

<br />
Don't ask about loot.  99.9% of the time, we don't know who's getting what.  We don't know who's dropping what.  So basically, you've taken your time to type out a question there's no way for us to know the answer to.  Additionally, you've forced the person you sent a tell to (you DID send it in a tell, didn't you?) to take time to respond "Fuck if I know" to a question you asked when you KNEW he didn't know the answer.  Unless it's a raid for a specific drop for a specific person (which is pretty rare) we don't know who's getting new gear.  You'll know when we know.</span><br /><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
